Global Household Financial Dynamics — Excel Portfolio Project

About This Project-

This is one of my first end-to-end Excel projects, built as part of 
my transition from a life sciences background into data analytics.

I picked this dataset because household financial data felt close to 
real business problems. The goal was not just to clean 
data and make pivot tables, but to ask real questions and find 
answers that someone non-technical could understand.

What I Did-

Started with a raw Kaggle dataset of 4,985 household records across 
5 countries — Brazil, Germany, India, UK and USA.

Data Cleaning (Power Query)
Removed inconsistencies, standardised column formats and handled 
missing values before loading into the main sheet.

Calculated Columns (built manually in Excel)
- Savings Rate % — monthly savings as a proportion of net income
- Expense Ratio — expenses as a proportion of net income  
- Risk Flag — classified each household as Safe, Medium or High Risk
- Performance Flag — compared each household savings rate against 
  their country average to label them Outperformer, Normal or 
  Underperformer
- Scenario Columns — modelled what happens to savings if expenses 
  are cut by 5%, 10%, 15% and 20%

PivotTables
Built 3 pivot tables covering country-level comparison, 
family size impact on savings, 
how number of earners affects savings rate.

Advance Analysis Sheet-
Calculated country benchmarks, high risk counts and underperformer 
counts per country using COUNTIFS and AVERAGEIF formulas.

Scenario Model-
Tested how many High Risk households would become financially Safe 
if they reduced their monthly expenses by varying percentages.

Summary Dashboard
Built a single-sheet dashboard pulling everything together — KPI 
tiles, country comparison table, risk breakdown, earner effect, 
family size trend and key analyst insights.



What I Found-

A few things genuinely surprised me during this analysis:

- India has the lowest average income of all 5 countries but the 
  highest savings rate at 42%. That flips the assumption that higher 
  income always means better saving habits.

- Germany is the opposite — highest earner, lowest saver at 15.9%. 
  The cost of living explanation makes sense when you look at the 
  expense ratio data.

- Adding one more earner to a household makes a huge difference. 
  Single earner households save around $632 per month on average. 
  Three-earner households save $1,928. That is a 205% jump.

- Family size hurts savings more than I expected. A family of 8 
  saves at a 17% rate vs 41% for a family of 3 — nearly 63% less.

- 700 out of 966 High Risk households could turn financially Safe 
  just by cutting expenses by 20%. That felt like the most 
  actionable finding in the whole project.

